@section KDE

@strong{KDE3}:
Copy the wipefreespace.desktop file from the distribution tarball to
$KDEHOME/share/apps/konqueror/servicemenus/, creating the directory if necessary.
$KDEHOME is usually $HOME/.kde. Then, restart Konqueror. A new context menu entry
under the "Actions" submenu should be available for block devices and all files
(a filesystem can reside inside a regular file).
@sp 1

@strong{KDE4}:
Copy the wipefreespace-kde4.desktop file from the distribution tarball to
$HOME/.kde4/share/kde4/services/ServiceMenus/, creating the directory if necessary.
Then, restart Konqueror/Dolphin. A new context menu entry under the "Actions" submenu
should be available for block devices and all files
(a filesystem can reside inside a regular file).


@node Command line syntax and options, , KDE, Usage
@comment  node-name, next,      previous,  up
@section Command line syntax and options

Basic syntax is:

 wipefreespace [options] /dev/XY [...]

The '/dev/XY' part stands for a device with a supported file system. Examples: /dev/hda1, /dev/fd0.
More than one device can be given on the command line, but they will be wiped sequentially,
@strong{NOT} in multiple threads. WipeFreeSpace is not multi-threaded and probably won't be,
because the libraries used can be not thread-safe and the program can't tell if a library will
be used until it's used.

Each given filesystem is wiped @strong{ONLY ONCE}, no matter how many times
it appears on the command line.

WipeFreeSpace also works for file systems created inside regular files on any host file system.

@strong{NOTE}: It is best to use this program on un-mounted file systems,
which makes sure the journal is committed.

@strong{NOTE}: If a block is damaged, it is only wiped until the first error. There is
no guarantee that it will be fully wiped.

Options:

@noindent @option{--all-zeros}@*
@quotation
Use only zeros for wiping.
@end quotation

@noindent @option{--background}@*
@quotation
Continue work in the background, if possible. This disables verose mode.
@end quotation

@noindent @option{-b superblock_offset}@*@option{--superblock superblock_offset}@*
@quotation
Superblock offset on the given filesystems (usually detected automatically).
@end quotation

@noindent @option{-B block_size}@*@option{--blocksize block_size}@*
@quotation
Block size on the given filesystems (usually detected automatically).
@end quotation

@noindent @option{-f}@*@option{--force}@*
@quotation
Forces the program to do its job even when the file system has errors.
@end quotation

@noindent @option{-h}@*@option{--help}@*
@quotation
Print help and exit.
@end quotation

@noindent @option{--last-zero}@*
@quotation
Perform additional wiping with zeros.
@end quotation

@noindent @option{-l}@*@option{--license}@*@option{--licence}@*
@quotation
Print license information and exit.
@end quotation

@noindent @option{-n NNN}@*@option{--iterations NNN}@*
@quotation
Number of passes (must be greater than 0, default is 35 in Gutmann method, 25 in random).
This is also the number of patterns (including random) used to wipe the free space.
@end quotation

@noindent @option{--nopart}@*
@quotation
Do NOT wipe free space in partially used blocks.
@end quotation

@noindent @option{--nounrm}@*
@quotation
Do NOT wipe undelete information.
@end quotation

@noindent @option{--nowfs}@*
@quotation
Do NOT wipe free space on file system.
@end quotation

@noindent @option{--use-ioctl}@*
@quotation
Disable device caching during work (can be DANGEROUS). This requires
the fcntl.h header file and the ioctl() function to be present.
@end quotation

@noindent @option{-v}@*@option{--verbose}@*
@quotation
Enables verbose output. The program will tell what it's doing. Use twice for more.
This also enables progress bars, but be warned: these may not always be accurate or
increase at a constant rate.
@end quotation

@noindent @option{-V}@*@option{--version}@*
@quotation
Print version number and exit.
@end quotation

@strong{NOTE}: All three options @option{--nopart}, @option{--nounrm}, @option{--nowfs} must
@strong{NOT} be given at once. This would mean that no work must be done and the program will
exit with "Bad/missing command line syntax" error code.

@strong{NOTE}: Any option affects all filesystems given on the command line, not just
the ones following it.

